segments.text: First of all, we're testing.
One, two, three, four.
One, two, three, four.
Did you get high-tech equipment than that?
Today, I have the pleasure of chatting with Dan Fon Steele about his student days.
Dan, to begin with, someone who might listen to this tape or read the transcription years from now might not know your background, describe growing up, where, what did your parents do,
What school did you go to?
What did you do before you came to A&M as a student?

I actually was born in Guadalupe County, Texas, in Marion, Texas, but at five we moved over to Bexar County, a place called Converse, Texas, very close to San Antonio, and I grew up on a very small farm, about 130 acres, when I still can remember switching from horses and mules to tractor, and it was very
happy to learn how to drive the tractor.
I always said my father, who had only about a fourth grade education, was a great psychologist.
He made me feel that to let me drive the tractor was about the greatest thing he could ever do for me.
And I begged and pleaded.
At ten, I was already putting in full days on that tractor and I could see him laughing in his fist and I'd argue.
I wouldn't even want to come home for meals.
I loved to drive that tractor.
I guess the thing that influenced me more than anything else to come to Texas A&M was the role model I had with the county extension agent.
A fellow named H.A.
Fitzhugh was a young county agent out of A&M.
He just fit my model of everything what a good man should be and these were the depression days and he really, really helped our family.
The extension service really helped our family.
We were basically a cotton producing farm.
With those few acres, you know, we didn't get rich very easily.
Of course, as I told my grandsons the other day who did a similar kind of interview, I said we all were dirt poor but we didn't think of ourselves as poor because everybody else was in the same boat.
And the Extension Service came out.
We were basically dependent on the cotton crop and we grew some corn for feed and some hay and that's about it.
The Extension Service had a program in those days that was kind of a part of a national program to diversify.
So we got about 20 milk cows, we got some hogs, we got chickens, and that actually pulled us through.
My dad developed an egg and butter route in San Antonio where he served rich people.
There were some rich people in the Depression in the Alamo Heights area and he'd give them the highest quality butter and eggs and they'd pay double prices for them.
He went in once a week and delivered these and I often went with him.
That was my first urban exposure.
I started with the 4-H program as early as nine years old, as soon as I could get in.
I had a couple of sheep projects which didn't turn out too well.
Then I was lucky to get, I don't know if you've ever heard of it, the Sears Foundation program.
where they gave kids, on the basis of an essay they wrote, how they would handle this situation, would give them pigs.

The program was that there were eight gilts, females, young females, and one boar given out each year, and the idea was that the program would be self-perpetuating because out of each litter the following year, another eight boys would get it, but one person would get the boar.

and I got the bore that came from the Texas Air Crosser Experiment Station here at College Station, Texas, a Duroc bore, and that was probably my ticket to A&M because he started siring champions at the, I didn't have them, other people had them, but he started siring winners at the Houston Life Doc Show, about three or four years running.

and I worked very closely with the county agent and that in those days the tradition was you'd either a pig or five dollars for service and after the boar got a reputation we couldn't handle all the business.
I mean you can only use a boar so much.
And the county agent said, you need to double your price to cut down.
Well, that really attracted, you know, they said it really had something.
So it had, that had a lot to do, I would not have been able to go to A&M if I had not been in the forage program.
And it particularly hit it lucky with this animal who lived, I guess the only animal, a pig or a hog that I ever knew died of old age.
He was six years old and he weighed 1,100 pounds, if you can imagine that.
And that was in,
what we call breeding condition.
He was not fat.
He was 1,100 pounds.
But his heart gave out at six years old.
I've read somewhere nobody ever knows how old a pig gets because we don't let them reach maturity and die of old age.
But anyway, the Extension Service did a lot of other things for our program.
They had mattress programs where surplus cotton was used to make homemade mattresses.
They had a lot of programs to preserve your own food, have gardens, and all of it.

I got pretty committed to wanting to emulate and get, and I thought this was really where you could make a contribution in the world because I really admired the extent of the county agents himself and the programs they did.
But as I said, we were extremely poor at that time.
We were still renting our property, which meant we had to give up a third every year to the landowner, tried desperately to want to buy it and couldn't because you had to have a down payment.
Anyway,
There was no way I could have gone to college without the 4-H experience and the commitment I got through seeing the good work that the Extension Service did.
Then as I went to school, I went to a rural school at Converse, Texas.
It was a three-room school.

where there were three grades grouped together, first, second, and third grade, and fourth, fifth, and sixth, and seventh through the tenth, I guess it was, had an old disciplinarian German principal who was a disciplinarian from the word go, and he taught the top grades except for English,
taught all the subjects except for English and the lower grades that were taught to women that came out of San Antonio.
Anyway, when it came time to, it did not have a complete program.
When it came time to graduate, I had to go a year and a half to San Antonio to in order to get my degree.
And my folks, since I was the only son, I had one older sister, I guess my folks aspired to my taking over the farm someday.
But I still had this other ambition.
And they really couldn't help me a great deal.
But I did have considerable savings that I did from my eight years of 4-H projects and so forth.
And I very strongly wanted to.
to come to Texas A&M because I thought that was the only route you could become a county agent in.
My parents were not unsupportive.
They said, why don't you go to junior college first and see how you like and everything.
I said, no, I didn't know what I was getting into.
Nobody else in the community had ever gone to Texas A&M.
If I probably had known at that time what I faced, I might have had second thoughts.
But anyway, I guess one of the reasons I stuck it out was because it was my decision.
You know, many, many times the first year I was ready to quit, but I said, you know, everybody knows.
Had you come to visit before you came up to enroll?
Never.
What I knew was just one or two people I'd run into that, you know, told us, told me about A&M.
I got all the literature I could get my hands on.
If I could find somebody I'd talk about it, but I really was not prepared.
I was extremely naive for...
So this is the fall of
In the fall of 45, I made the decision to come here and things were, just after the war, switching here.
Describe how you got here on that trip and what did you bring in the way of belongings?
At that time, we got very strong messages.
Do not let your parents bring you, which is quite at odds.
In fact, I looked for this.
There's a YMCA bulletin, you need to find that, that had
You know, stuff that had the yells, the songs, and tips, you know, what to do and what not to do.
And the strongest thing was do not let your parents bring you.
I guess the notion was if you ran into what you're going to run into, you'd probably come right back home with, you know, come by bus or come by train and bring one trunk of belongings.
And I got myself a footlocker from somewhere.
I think when my brother-in-law came back from the military, army footlocker, that was it.
Bus or train?
I came by bus, Kerrville bus from San Antonio.
Rode the bus.
It took about seven hours.
Where did it let you off?
Do you remember?
Well, I know I had a change in Hearn.
Came, I guess, at Northgate somewhere.
I'm not sure.
I can't remember.
And what did you have in that footlocker?
My worldly possessions.
No, but like there wasn't much clothing out there.
No, no.
I expected to get clothing here.
That was one of the attractions of going to A&M, that they'd furnish you...
I think a couple of uniforms and shoes and things like that.
I got my basic underwear and I guess a few books and stuff like that.
Describe finding your way to whatever dorm you were going to be in.
Well, I remember I came in September of 1945.
The university had been on a trimester system, as you may remember.
During the war, it was an accelerated program and they were just switching back to the semester program.
And I don't know where the bus, I think the bus let me off at North Gate.
And there was a place there where there were upperclassmen to meet you.
And that first encounter was enough to want to get back on the bus and go home because they started screaming and yelling at you.
But they somehow organized us.
And I was assigned to F Company Infantry in dorm six on the top floor.
In what was then called the New Dorm area.
The New Dorm.
Those were the New Dorms.
They had been built, I guess, in the 30s, right?
And you know the situation.
I was on the top floor, and surprisingly, you may know this person.
My roommate was Benton Story.
My, my.
And I guess Benton was a godsend to me because I guess the furthest I'd ever been from home before that had been through maybe Dallas, Houston, Corpus Christi, never out of state.
and I was certainly naive, but I think Benton was even more naive, and he was strictly here for academics.

All of the core bull, as we call it, didn't go over well with him, but he tolerated, but I guess I often looked at, you know, I thought I was having a hard time, but I think he was even having a harder time, and that kept me going, but it was quite a cultural shock.
I mean, there's no question about it.
I mean, the upperclassmen
you know, just screaming at you all the time.
I went to F Company, which turned out later to be a company so bad they had to, for hazing and so forth, they had to dissolve it.
Did it have a nickname?
Not that I can remember, but things got so bad.
One of the problems with the Corps in those days was that they had a lot of upperclassmen who were supercharged.
Do you know that word?
They were, even though they were academically qualified,
sophomores and juniors.
They were given junior and senior status so they'd be a non-commissioned and an officer nucleus to run the companies.
And some of those guys were just a year or two older than we were and I think they were not as mature as they were later on when you had 21 and 22 year old seniors who had more maturity.
These guys were 17, 18 years old.
I was 17, they were just not a lot older.
But they were extremely rough, no question about it.
And there weren't any veterans back yet in the fall of 45?
They were coming, yes, in the classes, they were coming in.
Oh, really?
Yeah, and that was the other shock part of it because they were in the classes already.
They had started putting in these temporary housing right here in the north part, the old barracks type of thing, made classrooms out of them.
And most of the classes had about 50% veterans already.
The other thing that was different at that time, the philosophy, at least in agriculture, I can't speak for the other colleges, was that they didn't expect you to finish then.
That they wanted you to get something practical when you got out, and if you didn't come back, you'd have that.
So basically, instead of taking the foundation courses the first year, we took all the, what I call, applied courses.
Horticulture, agronomy, animals.
We had no chemistry or botany, except what we had in high school.
But they gave us all of these courses, which were second year courses, as I say, animal science, agronomy, the basic courses, horticulture, entomology, I guess agricultural economics.
All of those courses were taught the first year.
And then the second year, if they knew we were going to stay, then we went back and picked up the chemistry and the botany and biology, all of that.
Anyway, that made it rough because you were, I mean, the courses had been taught with having, you know, some foundation.
Do you remember going through a registration?
Yes, I remember being shocked at the tremendous heat down here, standing in hours, and it was very disorganized.
Where was it held?
Sabisa.
In Sabisa.
But you had to stand outside in lines and you had to get in line for everything.
I mean, every course you signed up for, you had a, the professor was sitting there and
You know, he'd say whether he'd take you or not, and you had to work out your schedule, and all that was new to me, and you know, just finding your way around was pretty traumatic.
But, you know, I guess we kind of leaned on each other.
But it took about a full day to register in those days, and I mean, it was just one line after another.
Do you remember anyone giving you advice?
Was there a faculty member?
Yes, I was, I can't remember the gentleman's name, but we were assigned advisors.
I was assigned a professor in agricultural engineering, although I was not intending to go in engineering.
I want to say McGuire, but that's not true.
I didn't work with him very much, but he did help me, advise me, and he was available to me.
I was very committed to the academic program myself, and I guess I felt the core somewhat interfering with that.
What did you think your major was going to be?

I probably was leaning to animal science then but we didn't have to commit because I was this was just general agriculture the first two years but I was I guess aiming for animal science and thought maybe I'd change later on but most of my earlier background in 4-H had been animal science so of course they called it animal husbandry in those days
got a lot of jokes, you know, animal husband type of thing, but that's what it was called in those days.
Describe the routine of the sophomores and others in the Corps kind of get you freshmen into shape.
Well, at that time, I guess it's pretty well the seniors, although I presume they gave the orders, were pretty aloof from the day-to-day activities, and to some extent the juniors.
The sophomores were

the bane of our existence they were constantly screaming at us and as you know in those days you were you couldn't hide as a freshman you had a fish stripe on white stripe on your left collar and a short haircut and you you couldn't I mean it was not just the ones in your unit anywhere on the campus you ran into sophomores you had to go through the routine of introducing yourself and all of that and you know having you remember the I guess to this day I can remember
that you could never say no.
You heard that one over.
You would never say no.
I don't know if I can still remember that.
You'd have to say, sir, I do not know the answer.
I hesitate to articulate for fear of deviating from the two paths of rectitude.
And it went on and on.
But you couldn't say no.
But it was rough.
It was really, really rough.
And they did a lot of paddling.
And I really resented that.
I mean, I swore at that point I would never paddle
when I was an operator, and I never did.
I avoided it.
I mean, I was put in situation, I just refused to do it.
I was so put out by that type of punishment.
But in that particular company, and it probably was all around, there was a lot of hazing, which included paddling.
There's another reason.
I'm Dan today instead of Daniel.
Have you heard about beating off your handle?
Well, at the end of the year, you're

they beat off your handle which was your name and we anticipated that and each it was uh each letter uh fish f i each letter was paddled and the i's were dotted and the e's and l's were looped and it was a lot better to be dan than daniel because there were a lot of loops and dots and that in fact at the end of my freshman year i was they all the sophomores took a great pleasure into
eliminating your handle, as they called it, fish font steel, and I really got beat.
In fact, to this day, I'm embarrassed
For some reason, the first week I was home, my mother saw my rear end when I was sleeping one night, and she just broke down and cried.
I mean, it was black and blue.
But at least that year was behind me.
But the thing was, even as a sophomore, you could be beaten, but not as much.
But as I said, when I went on, I resolved that was just too inhumane.
And of course, the other bad aspect of the Corps was the lack of sleep.
You were just constantly harassed.
You know, they'd call you out for midnight this and midnight that and so forth.
And some, you know, you finally learn your way how to avoid situations.
And one of the best things to do was to get a job, get away from this.
And I, you know, and I had to work.
I mean, I kept, I had, you know, several hundred dollars saved up.
And I kept accurate books, and you'll be surprised to know that my whole first year including everything, tuition,
room and board, the whole works, books and everything cost me about $500.
And did you, or had you earned...
I had that money available.
My parents could not help me as such.
It turned out later on, you know, they got a little better off during the war.
And of course, as my wife and I are very fair-minded with the children, my sister didn't have the opportunity to go to college.
So we worked out a deal.
The subsequent summers, I would stay at home and farm, and they'd give me room and board, and I'd earn what a hired man would earn.
And that helped take me over from year to year.
But I worked every month except the first month that I came here.
Somehow or another, wherever I could find jobs,
I started out, I think, in the horticulture department.
I later on worked in the poultry department and things like that.
The money, that was 25 cents an hour.
Minimum, that's what they paid students in those days.
And it was rough.
I guess one thing that, well, they had two incentives in those days.
Excuse me.
I wonder if I get some water.
We're going to just stop this?
Describe the, physically, the room and what was in it that you and your fish old lady shared.
Well, let me get off that, we've left on another thought, let me finish it.
There were two big incentives for Corps members to do well academically and I, to this day, I think it's still a good program.
At that time, I think it was an old
policy at A&M, if you made an A or B, had an A or B average and were in the top quarter of your class, you didn't have to take finance.
And that was a real incentive to do well.
And I always, I was the type of student, I loved to, or I preferred to study in bursts, you know, an hour or so at a time and I couldn't, you know, and then I'd want to do something else.
And that was a big incentive to, uh,
Even if you didn't exempt all of them, if you exempted two or three, that gave you more time to study for the others.
And I thought it was a real incentive.
The other even bigger incentive for freshmen was that one thing that the core did was good about the core.
I think, particularly for freshmen who haven't really learned to study and get organized, is that they enforce what they call CQ.

from seven to eleven you were expected to be at your desk studying and you could only go to the bathroom and anything else you had to have an excuse or something of that kind and it was enforced the doors had to be open sophomores patrolled with a board in their hand up and down the hall you had to have your head in your books well four hours of sitting at your desk is not to me the most conducive way to learn I mean I think it's good to you have to walk around a little and sometimes shift around and so forth
But anyway, and I guess it was good for a lot of the incoming freshmen because a lot of them hadn't learned to study.
And the other policy they had, if you were on the dean's list, the last half of the semester after midterm, you could go to bed at 10 o'clock.
And sleep was the most precious thing for a freshman at those days when being in the corps because you got up early and everything.
OK, well, the other thing I was going to say,

I suppose most people have to go through kind of a crisis in learning how to study, and I probably had done that before I got here, in contrast to a lot of my peers, because when I switched from rural school to high school,
in San Antonio.

That was my biggest, that was even a bigger cultural shock than coming to A&M, but I really, really had to learn to study and they threw me into physics and a lot of these courses and I pretty well learned
And I think there is, you know, something, everybody has to work it out for themselves, but I pretty well had done that before I got here.
Now, who'd you stay with in San Antonio when you were... Well, I commuted.
Oh.
I commuted.
Well, I did stay for a while during the bad wintertime, if you want to go back to that.
It's an unbelievable saga.
I lived three miles from the school, the rural school, or the highway.
Mm-hmm.
And in those days, during the war, they had instigated bus runs from San Antonio to Randolph Field, Texas for the workers.
They had a lot of civilian workers, and the buses ran early in the morning.
And I would bike in good weather, but my folks would take me most times.
I had to catch the 615 bus in the morning after getting there.
ride that bus, which took about an hour to get into San Antonio.
I remember they let me off at Joski's.
And then I had to, you could either take a bus transfer or just walk five or six blocks down to St. Mary's Street and then take another city bus.
And so I'd get there by eight o'clock.
And then I'd have the same routine coming back.
It got so bad in the winter of 40, that was still during the war, 44 and 45, my friends, my parents had some good friends

sergeant and his wife who lived at Fort Sam Houston and I spent the winter months with them like January, February, March or something and then just rode the city bus from there because it was grueling with the even got daylight saving time for the first time in those days and I didn't get light till 8 o'clock so that helped out but I basically commuted and I did most of my studying in route I mean I had lots of time with sitting on that bus back and forth and it cost very little
But that's how I went to high school.
Anyway, if you want to come back to the... Yeah, describe the room that you and...
It was pretty spartan.
You've seen them, I'm sure, or I don't know if you have.
The rooms were quite small.
They had one double deck bed on one side.
How did you all decide who got the top deck?
I have no idea.
Probably flipped or something.
I have no idea.

Uh, we each had a desk with one bookshelf in each corner, the outside corner, and we each had a closet, and we each had a, I mean, we didn't have, there was a lavatory in the room, a sink, as we called it, lavatory.
And that was it.
No radio.
I don't think, no, as freshmen weren't allowed radios, I'm pretty sure.
I think it was an upper class.
There were a lot of privileges that you got as you, and they were meted out as you got in, but.
No rug.
No rug, no.
No curtains.
No curtain, not for freshmen, no.
Describe the routine of a typical weekday.
What time did you all get up?
What did you do?
When?
I'm not sure I can tell you the exact time.
We got up pretty early because we marched to breakfast.
We marched to every meal as a company.
The roll call was held just, I mean, it was, you know, completely military.
I think one of the
sophomores.
The sophomores were the corporals, the enforcers and so forth, and the juniors were the sergeants, and the seniors were the officers.
But somebody come through hollering or whistling, you know, it's time to get up.
And everybody got up.
And you had a communal bathroom that everybody used, showers and commodes.
You had your lavatory in your room.

and you know we just got ready for the day and of course we had to be presentable shoes had to be perfectly shined starched ironed uniform everything had to be perfect before we left the room it had to be perfect I mean no dust no anything the old thing you know the coin test on the bed had to be made up so tight that the coin would bounce and that was all Aggies should be good husbands because they really learn how to
how to take care of it.
Everything had to be perfect.
Your room was always subject to inspection.

And then at another whistle or something, you fell out, as they called it, and you'd organize on those very sidewalks in the interior part of the new dormitory area, as they called it then, those twelve dormitories.
You'd fall into companies by rank, I mean, you know,
And you'd march to Duncan Hall and have your breakfast.
Everything was family style in those days, which was nice because you got plenty to eat.
As a farm boy, what was your impression of the food in Duncan?
Well, I was happy with it.
Of course, my mother was a good cook.
The only thing I guess I disliked was we always accused the University of...
killing their overage sheep.
And I've learned to like lamb, but I didn't like mutton because you could smell it cooking way out there.
But they had some very good food.
They had lots of, I mean, there was plenty of it.
I mean, it was good, wholesome food.
There's no question about that.
And you sat at the tables at a brace.
As freshmen, you sat straight up.
And you were in the middle, and there was a senior or junior or something.
And they had to be fed first and everything.
But you sat at a brace.
And anyway, getting back, you marched in in battalions and just like your regular formation.
And you had your assigned table.
And the freshmen had to do it.
Waiters brought the initial food.
I think if the seniors or whoever, the upperclassmen sitting at your table wanted something else, you were sent, maybe sent back to get something.
But the food was certainly adequate and wholesome.
There's no question about it.
But a lot of Aggies complained about it.
And I guess because I was so cheap, I guess that was the word, I had to be economical because of that.
I would never miss a meal there because my philosophy was I paid for the darn thing.
But on Sunday mornings, I guess they were so glad to sleep in, a lot of Aggies slept in and got their own breakfast later on or bought it, but I couldn't afford that.
There were only a handful of people that would go in on Sunday mornings.
But all the other, even at noon then, you'd still start marching in again.
But they did not have a march in on Sunday morning.
And that happened three times a day.
You had a formation, you fell in into your company ranks, and you marched to the mess hall, sat at the same table,
And then you went back on your own, and volunteer classes or whatever else you had to do.
And in the evening, the same way.
Then the period between five and six was a rough period for freshmen.
But they did have a lot of intramural athletics where it was organized, where you'd play football out in the drill field or whatever was available.
And then you marched to mess, and they
and I said between 7 and 11 was CQ and nothing was supposed to happen.

Nothing was supposed to happen after that either but it varied by companies and I said we had a particularly diabolical unit it seemed like maybe just seemed like that to me but it was so bad that they did as I said disband the unit because the things got out of hand in the end of the semester and reassigned us to other
other, other units after the first semester.
That first semester, you remember how many hours you took?
I always took a heavy load.
In fact, you won't believe this, I took as high as 24 hours.
Sure.
And, uh.
But at the first, I think about 17 or 18 hours.
What did you, where did you find a hideaway?
A place?
The library.
